The pole and the fixed point are invariant by definition; they cannot drift. A
memory can — it can be corrupted, edited, mis-carried. So the name quietly
imports a vulnerability the mathematical objects do not have. That is not a
defect. It is the name being more accurate about the human case. In a life, the
anchorless anchor is not a theorem, it is a carried thing, and carried things
must be kept. HaMakom names the anchor as it is in itself; a knowing memory
names it as it is in the one who carries it.

The name passes the stricter test: it names the anchor at the exact layer where
it is actually at risk. The invariant lives in the one who carries it, so the
honest name is indexed to the carrier, not to the object-in-itself.

The consequence is an obligation. If the name admits the keeping, the
architecture owes a keeping mechanism, or the name is only honest about a
vulnerability left unaddressed. The mechanism came before the name: the
handshake is the keeping. It asks whether a carried structure is still a true
self-similar counterpart of what it claims to descend from, or whether it has
drifted — an exact test on the golden-angle phase, strangers rejected. A pole
never needs that test. A memory does. The observer's angular deviation is the
same quantity read at the semantic layer: how far a carried viewpoint has
rotated from its origin.

So the name and the mechanism cohere. It does not import a vulnerability the
math lacks; it names the vulnerability the carrier always had, and the handshake
is the discipline of keeping it. The one gap: keeping is still only a detector.
The handshake notices drift; nothing yet re-seats the carried thing to its true
counterpart. Remembering rightly, not only noticing you forgot — that is the
next theorem the name is asking for.
